,"indent":[]}},{"type":"link","title":null,"url":"https://wiki.python.org/moin/GlobalInterpreterLock","children":[{"type":"text","value":"gil","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":335,"offset":736},"end":{"line":8,"column":338,"offset":739},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":334,"offset":735},"end":{"line":8,"column":391,"offset":792},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" but blocking operations such as this can run simultaneously: when we have http socket waiting for the response python can skip the waiting in the current thread and move the next thread, this way we can have almost the full concurrency. This mechanic will eventually slow down on a large scale because of the CPU load and also slower as the process concurrency model. This is the part where celery flexibility comes in place. We can start celery in multiprocess mode by supplying ","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":391,"offset":792},"end":{"line":8,"column":872,"offset":1273},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">-c</code>","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":872,"offset":1273},"end":{"line":8,"column":876,"offset":1277},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":"(concurrency) flag and supply the number of processes to spawn, that way we will utilize the whole number of server cores. By default, celery will start workers with the process number equal to the number of server` cores. Because i wanted to also utilize the thread concurrency model i started workers a little bit different:","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":876,"offset":1277},"end":{"line":8,"column":1202,"offset":1603},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1,"offset":402},"end":{"line":8,"column":1202,"offset":1603},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","lang":"shell","meta":null,"value":"<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\">$: <span class=\"token keyword\">for</span> <span class=\"token for-or-se